{
  "answer": "**In Charles Comte's *Traité de la propriété: VOL I* (1834), Chapter 4 (\"De l'occupation des choses\" / \"On the occupation of things\"), the author ridicules jurists' theory of a prior universal right over all things (leading to a supposed global contract of renunciation), which he calls a \"chimera.\"**[^1]\n\nHe argues that such a right would require implausibly convening all humanity for permission to use local resources, then provides this cascade of geographic examples:\n\n> By what reasoning would one have succeeded in demonstrating to **an inhabitant of Peru that he could not pick the fruit that grew at his hand, without infringing upon the rights of the inhabitants of Siberia**? How would one have made **an inhabitant of Kamchatka understand that he could not clothe himself in the skin of an animal, without injuring the rights of the Arabs**? How would one have gone about showing **the Gauls that they could not, in conscience, bring the plains of Auvergne under cultivation, without having obtained the permission of the inhabitants of Tibet**?[^1]\n\nComte deems the supposed contract equally absurd, as it is \"impossible\" and \"unintelligible,\" needing constant renewal for new generations, and contrary to evident human needs and progress.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/04-de-loccupation-des-choses/translation/#p-5f2b15).",
